  "prompt": "What causes cotton fabric to shrink? Heated water, cool water or both?",
  "response": "Cotton fabric shrinks primarily due to exposure to heat and moisture. When cotton fibers are washed, especially in hot water, they can swell and become more relaxed. Upon drying, particularly with heat, the fibers can contract, leading to shrinkage.\n\nTo summarize:\n\n- **Heated water**: This is a significant factor in cotton shrinkage because the heat causes the fibers to expand and then, when dried, to contract.\n- **Cool water**: Generally, using cool or cold water can minimize shrinkage because it does not cause the fibers to swell as much.\n\nIn conclusion, while both heated water and cool water can affect cotton, heated water is the main contributor to shrinkage.",
